description.narrative: Public Action for Resilience (PAR) will work with at-risk communities and vulnerable groups.to address the pull factors to violent extremism, which include the.radicalization of youth through social media and the recruitment of.Azerbaijanis as foreign terrorist fighters through formal and social recruitment.networks. The activity will focus on youth in high-risk areas identified by the.U.S. government's 2017 Azerbaijan Violent Extremism Risk Assessment. PAR will improve the capacity of existing Azerbaijani government-supported Youth Houses as part of an effort to build social cohesion and resilience to bring.community members together. The activity will empower vulnerable youth through.skills and vocational training, and income-generating activities with the goal.of increasing their resilience to violent extremism and radicalization. Through.the activity, community and religious leaders will be trained to identify.potential extremist warning signs, and how to facilitate engagement between.community members and connect them to services that can mitigate extremist push.and pull factors. Community engagement will identify grievances to guide the.implementation to mitigate the influence of extremist groups, and address risk.factors that allow extremist ideology to take root.

description.narrative: (Azerbaijan): .The Private Sector Activity (PSA), through partnership and.co-investment, supports a more resilient Azerbaijani economy and improves the.enabling environment for private investment. PSA's main objectives and.components include: 1) developing a more diversified non-oil economy through.initiatives that assist micro, small, and medium agribusinesses and farmers; 2).improving the enabling environment for private investment; 3) empowering women.in business; 4) supporting the non-oil sector by improving the competitiveness.of the private sector, with a special emphasis on agriculture and tourism; and,.5) reducing administrative barriers that hinder the development of Micro, Small.and Medium Enterprises (MSMEs). ..With FY 2022 resources, PSA will continue to empower and.enhance women-run, women-led, and women-focused businesses and professional.associations to advocate for an improved business-enabling environment for.women entrepreneurs, including improving their employment conditions throughout.Azerbaijan. With FY 2022 resources, USAID/Azerbaijan will continue to.advocate for improvements in the business-enabling environment for women.entrepreneurs to access resources that assist them with overcoming.gender-driven obstacles. The activity increases Azerbaijan's economic.development and diversification while building ties with American businesses.(ICS Goal 2.2, JSP 2.1, CAATSA Goal 8). The Mission plans to extend this.activity for one additional year and increase its ceiling by $3.5 million to.expand activities that will help minimize Azerbaijan's dependence on Russian.markets. The wheat value chain will be added to the assisted value chains to.support Azerbaijan's food security; and the development and growth of the.Middle Corridor, a major transit route between Europe and Asia will be.supported. ..

description.narrative: (Azerbaijan): .FY 2021 resources will be used to support a forthcoming governance activity entitled Social Engagement Support (SES), building off of the ten-year Socio-Economic Development Activity, to be awarded by the end of FY 2021. The SES activity will be a five-year, approximately$15M activity geared towards fostering citizen-government dialogue to address local issues, reduce community vulnerabilities, and increase community resilience to identified sources of vulnerability, including those of a socio-economic nature. USAID will seek to integrate the Agency's private sector engagement approach to include the private sector as a critical stakeholder in community dialogues with local government and central level government as appropriate. The new activity will utilize a community-engagement approach that prioritizes democratic governance and will leverage private sector networks and resources to enhance access to quality and sustainable service delivery. The activity will support rural Azerbaijani citizens to become increasingly independent (ICS Goal 3.1), promote stability in vulnerable areas (ICS Goal 1.2, JSP 1.3), and grow an increasingly productive rural economy (ICS Goal 2.2, JSP 2.2). .

description.narrative: Assist special populations which may be vulnerable or at-risk on a temporary or chronic basis whose needs are not addressed under emergency humanitarian assistance or other programs. These include groups such as the disabled; orphans, children and at-risk youth; victims of trafficking; victims of gender-based violence; refugees, returnees, ethnic minorities, internally displaced or other socially excluded groups; the elderly; and female heads of household. Depending on circumstances, services may intend to protect groups; mitigate adverse conditions they face, or to remove barriers to help integrate them into society. Components may include measures to increase the capacity of local service and advocacy NGOs and/or professional social workers; to establish public/private service delivery partnerships as well as family and community focused service models; to establish effective referral networks; to develop appropriate service protocols and methods for screening prospective recipients; or to improve public understanding and sensitivity to the needs of the vulnerable. While services provided should not exclude victims of trafficking in persons, programs designed specifically for this group fall under the Peace and Security Objective under the Transnational Crime Area and the Trafficking in Persons and Migrant Smuggling Element.

description.narrative: (Azerbaijan): .USAID's Socio-Economic Development Activity.(SEDA) promotes civic participation and good governance in rural Azerbaijan..SEDA increases citizen participation in the political decision-making processes.at the local level to build government and civil society partnerships while.demonstrating America's long-term commitment to the government and people of.Azerbaijan. Communities learn to identify, prioritize, and implement small.infrastructure projects in collaboration with the local and central government.where appropriate, that provide a social or economic community benefit. Infrastructure.projects are tangible, but secondary to the primary outcome of developing.grassroots processes and skills of citizens to organize to improve their own.communities. The activity also contributes to USAID's CVE strategy by.addressing rural vulnerabilities related to lack of opportunity for civic.participation and lack of livelihoods. ..SEDA provides employment to vulnerable populations.and prioritizes support for initiatives that have local social and economic.impact by introducing new practices for citizens working together with.government to address development priorities at the community level. The.activity is currently implemented in Guba, Aran, Ganja-Gazakh, Sheki-Zagatala,.Lankaran, and Upper Garabagh regions. USAID's June 2019 data mapping proved.that these are the same locations that correlate with places of origin of many.of the foreign terrorist fighters who previously traveled to fight with ISIS..SEDA is designed to address livelihoods and civic participation, which address.key drivers identified in an interagency violent extremism assessment..The activity will support rural Azerbaijani.citizens to become increasingly independent (ICS Goal 3.1), promote stability.in vulnerable areas (ICS Goal 1.2, JSP 1.3), and promote an increasingly.productive rural economy (ICS Goal 2.2, JSP 2.2). ...

description.narrative: The overall goal of the project is to improve the business enabling environment for the development of micro and small enterprises (MSE) in Azerbaijan. The projects objectives are: (i) improve the dialogue and interaction between the state and civil society on issues affecting the development of MSEs; (ii) improve the legislative and institutional framework for the MSE enabling environment; (iii) provide practical assistance to MSEs, in particular for women-owned, family businesses to improve their viability and successful development. Policy related activities on MSME enabling environment are undertaken in five main directions: study of the problems of MSE and policy recommendations; legislative framework on business enabling environment; institutional framework on business enabling environment; mechanism of the protection of MSE from bureaucratic arbitrariness; increasing the competitiveness of MSE.The project is implemented by the alliance of six local NGOs and think tanks.

description.narrative: The Youth Business Leadership project provides internships at high profile companies to third and fourth year university students, conducts professional development workshops; and provides internship and mentorship opportunities with successful businessmen and businesswomen. BP provides funding support equal to USAIDs share, gives general recommendations and provides oversight to the Projects progress particularly in the process of selecting interns and internship positions and matching interns with mentors, and ensuring that the project meets its objectives. The American Chamber of Commerce provides support in identifying internship opportunities and mentors and in placing three months long internships at high profile companies. The implementer of the project, Junior Achievement Azerbaijan (JAA), has already provided workshops and internships to 75 students from four universities in Baku out of life of the project target of 120 students.

description.narrative: (Azerbaijan): USAID's Economic Empowerment for Entrepreneurship and Employment (E4) activity promotes economic and social participation of rural women and youth employment through improved job search skills and networking at employment centers. Additionally, it addresses the root causes of GBV by increasing access to services for women and improving knowledge, evidence and advocacy while increasing women's economic independence. With FY 2022 resources, E4 will continue to train vulnerable women and GBV survivors in business and vocational skills and provide them with small grants so they can establish their own businesses. This assistance will continue in all 11 Women Resource Centers that E4 assists nationwide. E4 will also continue youth training in soft skills, vocational skills, and English language in three youth professional growth centers established in Azerbaijan. These trainings assist senior students or recent university graduates with acquiring knowledge and skills training, as well as providing networking and support as they seek employment. ...

title.narrative: Mid-term Performance Evaluation of the Azerbaijan Strengthening Health Systems through Integrated Programs

description.narrative: IBTCI has been contracted to conduct a mid-term evaluation of the AZ SHIP project covering the project implementation period of September 27, 2011 to October 1, 2012. The purpose of this evaluation is to determine the effectiveness and timeliness of the project in achieving its strategic and technical approaches. The project under evaluation was expected to improve governance, financing, and resource mobilization of the health system, thus contributing to increased quality, accessibility, and efficiency of health care services for the entire population, using a diagonal approach that concurrently addresses vertical service delivery in three program elementsMNCH, RH/FP, and TBalong with preventive services. The evaluation gauges the willingness and ability of MOH to institutionalize and sustain AZ SHIP activities at the end of the project in September 2013. This was a qualitative performance evaluation which drew its sample from the population of stakeholders in Baku and all seven districts where AZ Ship is being implemented, namely: Absheron, Agdash, Gabala, Gakh, Ismayilli Sheki, and Zagatala. The Evaluation Team applied a mixed-methods approach that allowed them to solicit information from a variety of data sources to reveal findings that might not have surfaced otherwise and to triangulate information from different sources.

title.narrative: Azerbaijan Trade and Investment Reform Support Program (TIRSP)

description.narrative: By helping Azerbaijan accede to the World Trade Organization (WTO) and supporting business climate reform, the Azerbaijan Trade and Investment Reform Support Program (TIRSP) helped encourage economic growth through increased trade & investment in the non-oil sector. TIRSP provided technical assistance and training to accelerate the accession of the Government of Azerbaijan to the WTO. The program worked with the government to design accession-related legislative packages in areas such as customs valuation, rules of origin guidelines, tariff bindings, import/export control requirements, trade remedies, SPS-related legal and policy reforms, service sector market access, public procurement reforms and general subsidy/countervailing duty legislation, among others.
